---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "First Home Budget Planner: Calculate Your True Buying Power",
  "description": "Calculate how much house you can afford based on your income, debts, and the 28/36 rule. See your maximum monthly payment and estimated home price.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "I Just Want To"
  }
};

export const meta = {
  title: "First Home Budget Planner | I Just Want To",
  description: "Calculate how much house you can afford based on your income, debts, and the 28/36 rule. See your maximum monthly payment and estimated home price.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="ijustwantto"
  title="First Home Budget Planner | I Just Want To"
  description="Calculate how much house you can afford based on your income, debts, and the 28/36 rule. See your maximum monthly payment and estimated home price."
  canonical="https://ijustwantto.live/first-home-budget-planner"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>First Home Budget Planner</h1>
      <p>Find out exactly how much house you can afford without becoming "house poor".</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Interactive Calculator -->
    <div class="calculator card">
      <div class="input-grid">
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="annual-income">Gross Annual Income ($)</label>
          <input type="number" id="annual-income" value="85000" min="10000" step="1000">
        </div>
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="monthly-debt">Total Monthly Debt ($)</label>
          <input type="number" id="monthly-debt" value="600" min="0" step="50">
        </div>
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="interest-rate">Estimated Mortgage Rate (%)</label>
          <input type="number" id="interest-rate" value="6.5" min="1" max="15" step="0.1">
        </div>
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="down-payment">Planned Down Payment ($)</label>
          <input type="number" id="down-payment" value="40000" min="0" step="1000">
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="results-container">
        <div class="result-header">Your Affordability Breakdown</div>

        <div class="results-grid">
          <div class="result-box highlight">
            <div class="result-label">Max Affordable Home Price</div>
            <div class="result-value" id="max-home-price">$0</div>
            <div class="result-sub">Based on a 36% Debt-to-Income limit</div>
          </div>

          <div class="result-box">
            <div class="result-label">Max Total Monthly Housing Payment</div>
            <div class="result-value" id="max-monthly-payment">$0</div>
            <div class="result-sub">Includes PITI (Principal, Interest, Taxes, Ins.)</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="dti-warning" id="dti-warning" style="display: none;">
          <strong>Warning:</strong> Your current monthly debt is too high to qualify for a standard mortgage at this income level. Focus on paying down debt first.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <p>Back to our main guide: <a href="/first-time-home-buyer-checklist">The Ultimate First-Time Home Buyer Checklist</a>.</p>

      <h2>How Much House Can You Actually Afford?</h2>
      <p>One of the biggest mistakes first-time home buyers make is relying entirely on their lender to tell them how much house they can afford. Lenders calculate your maximum borrowing power based on gross income and risk models, not on your personal lifestyle, retirement goals, or childcare costs. If you borrow the absolute maximum your lender approves you for, you risk becoming "house poor"—meaning a disproportionate amount of your income goes toward housing, leaving little left for everything else.</p>

      <p>To determine your true budget, you need to understand how lenders view your finances and then apply those metrics to your own comfort level.</p>

      <h2>The Golden Rule of Mortgages: The 28/36 Rule</h2>
      <p>Most financial advisors and conservative mortgage lenders use the <strong>28/36 Rule</strong> to calculate housing affordability. This rule states that:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>The 28% Rule (Front-End Ratio):</strong> No more than 28% of your <em>gross</em> monthly income (your income before taxes are taken out) should go toward your total housing expenses. "Total housing expenses" means PITI: Principal, Interest, Property Taxes, and Homeowners Insurance (plus HOA fees if applicable).</li>
        <li><strong>The 36% Rule (Back-End Ratio / DTI):</strong> No more than 36% of your gross monthly income should go toward <em>all</em> your debt obligations combined. This includes your new housing payment plus your existing auto loans, student loans, minimum credit card payments, and personal loans.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Our First Home Budget Planner above uses the 36% back-end DTI ratio (Debt-to-Income) as the primary limiting factor, as it is the most common hurdle for modern buyers who often have existing student or auto debt.</p>

      <h2>The PITI Breakdown</h2>
      <p>When you calculate your monthly housing budget, you must look beyond just the principal and interest of the loan itself. The acronym <strong>PITI</strong> represents the four components of a standard mortgage payment:</p>

      <ol>
        <li><strong>Principal:</strong> The portion of your payment that goes toward paying down the actual balance of the loan.</li>
        <li><strong>Interest:</strong> The fee the lender charges you for borrowing the money. In the early years of a 30-year mortgage, the vast majority of your payment goes toward interest.</li>
        <li><strong>Taxes:</strong> Local property taxes. Lenders usually divide your annual property tax bill by 12 and collect it monthly, holding it in an escrow account to pay the government on your behalf when it's due.</li>
        <li><strong>Insurance:</strong> Homeowners insurance (which protects against fire, theft, etc.) and Mortgage Insurance (PMI or CMHC) if your down payment is less than 20%. Like taxes, this is usually collected monthly into an escrow account.</li>
      </ol>

      <p>If you fail to account for taxes and insurance, you will drastically overestimate how much house you can afford. Depending on where you live, high property taxes can easily add hundreds of dollars to your monthly payment.</p>

      <h2>Hidden Costs of Homeownership to Budget For</h2>
      <p>Beyond your PITI payment, owning a home comes with ongoing costs that renters don't have to worry about. When setting your final budget, ensure you leave room for:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Maintenance and Repairs:</strong> The general rule of thumb is to budget 1% to 2% of your home's total value per year for maintenance. If you buy a $400,000 house, you should save $4,000 to $8,000 annually for things like HVAC servicing, roof repairs, and plumbing issues.</li>
        <li><strong>Utilities:</strong> Houses are usually larger than apartments, meaning higher heating, cooling, and electricity bills. You will also likely be responsible for water, sewer, and trash collection fees.</li>
        <li><strong>Furnishing and Equipment:</strong> A bigger space requires more furniture. You'll also need to purchase a lawnmower, snow shovel, ladders, and various tools.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Before locking in a purchase price, practice "paying" your new mortgage. If your current rent is $1,500 and your estimated new mortgage is $2,200, put that $700 difference into a savings account every month for a few months. If your budget feels painfully tight, you know you need to look at less expensive homes.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- FAQs -->
    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What happens if my Debt-to-Income (DTI) ratio is above 36%?</h3>
          <p>While 36% is the traditional benchmark for financial health, many lenders will approve mortgages with a DTI of up to 43% for conventional loans, and sometimes up to 50% for FHA loans, provided you have a strong credit score. However, maximizing your DTI leaves you highly vulnerable to financial emergencies.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Should I use my gross income or net income to calculate my budget?</h3>
          <p>Lenders use your <em>gross</em> income (before taxes) to calculate your ratios. However, for your personal budgeting and peace of mind, it is often wiser to calculate your housing budget based on your <em>net</em> income (take-home pay), as this represents the actual cash you have available to spend each month.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Does paying off a car loan increase how much house I can afford?</h3>
          <p>Yes, significantly. By eliminating a $400 monthly car payment, you free up $400 in your monthly DTI ratio. Because mortgage rates are spread over 30 years, freeing up $400 a month can increase your maximum affordable home price by tens of thousands of dollars.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const incomeInput = document.getElementById('annual-income');
      const debtInput = document.getElementById('monthly-debt');
      const rateInput = document.getElementById('interest-rate');
      const dpInput = document.getElementById('down-payment');

      const maxPriceEl = document.getElementById('max-home-price');
      const maxPaymentEl = document.getElementById('max-monthly-payment');
      const warningEl = document.getElementById('dti-warning');

      function formatCurrency(num) {
        return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD', maximumFractionDigits: 0 }).format(num);
      }

      function calculate() {
        const annualIncome = parseFloat(incomeInput.value) || 0;
        const monthlyDebt = parseFloat(debtInput.value) || 0;
        const interestRate = parseFloat(rateInput.value) || 0;
        const downPayment = parseFloat(dpInput.value) || 0;

        const monthlyIncome = annualIncome / 12;

        // Target max DTI is 36% for total debt, or 28% for front-end housing
        const maxTotalDebtPayment = monthlyIncome * 0.36;
        const maxHousingPaymentByDTI = maxTotalDebtPayment - monthlyDebt;
        const maxHousingPaymentByFrontEnd = monthlyIncome * 0.28;

        // The limiting factor is the lower of the two
        let maxAllowedHousingPayment = Math.min(maxHousingPaymentByDTI, maxHousingPaymentByFrontEnd);

        if (maxAllowedHousingPayment <= 0) {
          warningEl.style.display = 'block';
          maxPriceEl.textContent = "$0";
          maxPaymentEl.textContent = "$0";
          return;
        } else {
          warningEl.style.display = 'none';
        }

        // Estimate Taxes and Insurance as roughly 1.5% of home value annually (0.015/12 monthly)
        // Let P = home price, D = down payment
        // Loan = P - D
        // Monthly Payment = (P - D) * PMT_factor + P * (0.015 / 12)
        // Max Payment = P * PMT_factor - D * PMT_factor + P * 0.00125
        // Max Payment + D * PMT_factor = P * (PMT_factor + 0.00125)
        // P = (Max Payment + D * PMT_factor) / (PMT_factor + 0.00125)

        const r = (interestRate / 100) / 12; // monthly rate
        const n = 360; // 30 years

        // PMT factor for 1 dollar
        const pmtFactor = (r * Math.pow(1 + r, n)) / (Math.pow(1 + r, n) - 1);

        const estimatedTaxInsRate = 0.015 / 12; // Monthly factor for taxes/ins based on home value

        const maxHomePrice = (maxAllowedHousingPayment + (downPayment * pmtFactor)) / (pmtFactor + estimatedTaxInsRate);

        maxPriceEl.textContent = formatCurrency(Math.max(0, maxHomePrice));
        maxPaymentEl.textContent = formatCurrency(Math.max(0, maxAllowedHousingPayment));
      }

      incomeInput.addEventListener('input', calculate);
      debtInput.addEventListener('input', calculate);
      rateInput.addEventListener('input', calculate);
      dpInput.addEventListener('input', calculate);

      // Initial calculation
      calculate();
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }

    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }

    .calculator { max-width: 750px; margin: 2rem auto 3rem; }
    .input-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .input-group label { display: block; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .input-group input { width: 100%; padding: 0.8rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 6px; background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--card-bg) 50%, transparent); color: var(--text-primary); font-size: 1rem; }
    .input-group input:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); }

    .results-container { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--bg-color) 80%, white); padding: 2rem; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .result-header { font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; text-align: center; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .results-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1.5rem; }
    .result-box { text-align: center; padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 8px; background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .result-box.highlight { border-color: var(--accent-color); background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); }
    .result-label { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600; }
    .result-value { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 0.3rem; }
    .result-sub { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }

    .dti-warning { margin-top: 1.5rem; padding: 1rem; background: color-mix(in srgb, #ef4444 15%, transparent); border-left: 4px solid #ef4444; border-radius: 4px; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-primary); }

    .content-section { margin-bottom: 3rem; line-height: 1.7; }
    .content-section p { margin-bottom: 1.2rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .content-section h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .content-section h3 { font-size: 1.3rem; margin: 1.5rem 0 0.8rem; }
    .content-section ul, .content-section ol { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; }
    .content-section li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .content-section a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; }
    .content-section a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

    .faq-section { margin-top: 4rem; }
    .faq-section h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; text-align: center; }
    .faq-item { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-bottom: 1.5rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-item:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
    .faq-item h3 { font-size: 1.2rem; margin-bottom: 0.8rem; }
    .faq-item p { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; }

    @media (max-width: 650px) {
      .input-grid, .results-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
